ce:section.ce:para:
During the frictional tests, transfer films were developed on the surface of wear traces for the balls, which had an important influence on the frictional wear of the polymer composites [42,43]. Fig. 9
                         shows SEM images of the transferred film on the surface of the ceramic balls after friction. In Fig. 9(a), after rubbing against the pure PI, the abrasive chips are largely not observed on the surface of the upper specimen ball, which may have undergone tribological oxidation during the sliding process. The direct contact at the friction interface makes the coefficient of friction of pure PI larger, resulting in poor tribological properties. The addition of carbon quantum dots and molybdenum disulfide, on the other hand, promotes the transfer of the composite and some bonding with the ball interface [Fig. 9(b ∼ n)]. Thus, to a certain extent, it is possible to change from ball-to-material friction to counter-abrasion between the materials (see Fig. 10
                        ), resulting in a reduced wear rate and a lower coefficient of friction. It was found that after the friction experiment with 1 wt% CQDs/PI, the friction area on the surface of the upper specimen ball was covered by the transfer film and relatively uniform. The analysis suggests that perhaps the addition of carbon quantum dots effectively promoted the formation of lubrication film between PI and the balls, enabling the transfer film to bond more closely with the balls and finally forming a transfer film with lubricating properties. As a result, the friction coefficient and wear rate of the composite is lower.
